Occupation: Student (and student employee as writing tutor)
Exp_Guess: I think it was about memory, movement, and patterns- so how well people can remember patterns in movement. Maybe it was also about how standing up or sitting down affects memory, or about how well people can mirror movements.
Results_Guess: Based off my experience with the study (I did not answer any of the questions correctly and was not confident in my answers), I would guess the results would show that many people have trouble remembering patterns in movement. But maybe their memory is not always completely off- maybe a lot of people get the correct movement but on the wrong side, or the right side but the wrong movement.
Understanding: I watched the 3rd of the videos while standing, as I did with the 2nd video- I forget if there were instructions to just stand still for the 3rd video but I remember being confused, as if the 2nd video was accidentally replaying. Maybe instructions to keep standing for the 3rd video would help? Also, for the extracurricular activity section instructions, I believe the third column was labelled "second."
Strategies: I tried not to think too hard about the movement that comes next because, to be honest, I didn't catch hold of any patterns while watching, even though I tried at times. I thought that thinking/concentrating hard would just make me indecisive, so when it came time to make my movement, I just tried to let it come naturally and subconsciously to me.
Images: I thought they were clear. I interpreted them as: move the opposite side as the person on screen, and stand instead of sitting.

That people with more sports and outdoor experience can perform the movements with more accuracy.
